<main class="content">

<section id="data">

<h2>2.1 Data</h2>

<p>

Data are numerical observations collected in a systematic manner by assigning numbers or 
scores to the outcomes of variables.

</p>

</section>

<section id="raw">

<h2>2.2 Raw Data</h2>

<p>

Raw data refers to the originally collected data which has not been modified or transformed. 
Information collected through censuses, surveys, experiments and observations is known as raw data.

</p>

</section>

<section id="typesdata">

<h2>2.3 Types of Data According to Source</h2>

<p>There are two types of data:</p>

<ul>

<li>Primary Data</li>
<li>Secondary Data</li>

</ul>

<h3>Primary Data</h3>

<p>

Primary data are collected directly by the investigator for a specific purpose through observation,
measurement or experimentation.

</p>

<h3>Methods of Collecting Primary Data</h3>

<ul>

<li>Direct personal interviews</li>
<li>Indirect oral interviews</li>
<li>Information from correspondents</li>
<li>Mailed questionnaire method</li>
<li>Schedules through enumerators</li>
<li>Telephonic interviews</li>

</ul>

<h3>Secondary Data</h3>

<p>

Secondary data are compiled from records collected by others. These data are usually available 
in published or unpublished sources.

</p>

<h3>Sources of Secondary Data</h3>

<ul>

<li>Government publications</li>
<li>Committee reports</li>
<li>Research publications</li>
<li>Trade and technical journals</li>
<li>Chambers of commerce and banks</li>
<li>International organizations</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section>

<h2>Difference Between Primary and Secondary Data</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Primary Data</th>
<th>Secondary Data</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Collected by investigator directly</td>
<td>Collected from records of others</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Original data</td>
<td>Not original</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>More reliable</td>
<td>Less reliable</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Expensive and time consuming</td>
<td>Less expensive and faster</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Raw material</td>
<td>Finished product</td>
</tr>

</table>

</section>

<section id="grouped">

<h2>Grouped and Ungrouped Data</h2>

<h3>Grouped Data</h3>

<p>

When data values are arranged into class intervals to simplify analysis, it is called grouped data.

Example: 0–10, 11–20, 21–30

</p>

<h3>Ungrouped Data</h3>

<p>

Data that remain in their original form without grouping.

Example: 2, 4, 10, 15, 21

</p>

</section>

<section id="variable">

<h2>2.4 Variable</h2>

<p>

A variable is a characteristic that varies from observation to observation.

</p>

<div class="highlight">

Examples:

<ul>

<li>Temperature</li>
<li>Plant height</li>
<li>Crop yield</li>
<li>Soil nitrogen content</li>

</ul>

</div>

<h3>Observations (Variate)</h3>

<p>

The specific numerical values assigned to variables are called observations.

Example: Crop yield = 30 kg

</p>

</section>

<section id="typesvar">

<h2>2.5 Types of Variables</h2>

<h3>Quantitative Variables</h3>

<p>

Variables expressed numerically such as height, weight, and number of seeds.

</p>

<h3>Qualitative Variables</h3>

<p>

Variables expressed as categories rather than numbers.

Examples include color, taste, intelligence, and social class.

</p>

<h3>Continuous Variables</h3>

<p>

Variables that can take any value within a range.

Examples:

<ul>
<li>Height</li>
<li>Weight</li>
<li>Temperature</li>
<li>Rainfall</li>
</ul>

</p>

<h3>Discrete Variables</h3>

<p>

Variables that take only specific integer values.

Examples:

<ul>
<li>Number of students</li>
<li>Number of seeds</li>
<li>Number of leaves</li>
</ul>

</p>

</section>

<section id="population">

<h2>2.6 Population</h2>

<p>

Population refers to the complete set of all items or individuals under investigation.

</p>

Examples:

<ul>

<li>Total students in a college</li>
<li>Total houses in a village</li>
<li>Total books in a library</li>

</ul>

<h3>Census</h3>

<p>

When every unit of the population is studied, the process is called census or complete enumeration.

</p>

<h3>Parameter</h3>

<p>

A parameter is a numerical measure describing a population characteristic.

Examples:

<ul>
<li>Population Mean (μ)</li>
<li>Population Standard Deviation (σ)</li>
<li>Population Correlation (ρ)</li>
</ul>

</p>

</section>

<section id="sample">

<h2>2.7 Sample</h2>

<p>

A sample is a small portion of the population selected for analysis.

</p>

<h3>Sample Survey</h3>

<p>

When only a part of the population is investigated, it is called a sample survey.

</p>

<h3>Statistic</h3>

<p>

A statistic is a numerical measure describing a sample.

Examples:

<ul>
<li>Sample Mean (x̄)</li>
<li>Sample Standard Deviation (s)</li>
</ul>

</p>

</section>

<section id="nature">

<h2>2.8 Nature of Data</h2>

<p>Data may be classified based on time and place.</p>

<h3>Time Series Data</h3>

<p>

Data collected over time.

Example: Year-wise rainfall data.

</p>

<h3>Spatial Data</h3>

<p>

Data related to location.

Example: District-wise rainfall data.

</p>

<h3>Spatio-Temporal Data</h3>

<p>

Data related to both time and location.

Example: Monthly rainfall data for different districts.

</p>

</section>

</main>

